    <exercise xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="fs-id1596002" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2989879">  
      <para id="import-auto-id3355301">Assume one-fourth of the yield of a typical 320-kT strategic bomb comes from fission reactions averaging 200 MeV and the remainder from fusion reactions averaging 20 MeV.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1842424">(a) Calculate the number of fissions and the approximate mass of uranium and plutonium fissioned, taking the average atomic mass to be 238.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2668906">(b) Find the number of fusions and calculate the approximate mass of fusion fuel, assuming an average total atomic mass of the two nuclei in each reaction to be 5.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id3250319">(c) Considering the masses found, does it seem reasonable that some missiles could carry 10 warheads? Discuss, noting that the nuclear fuel is only a part of the mass of a warhead.</para>
